\begin_layout Subsection*
Areas and determinants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, the image of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is defined as the set of images of all the points in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T:A\to B$
\end_inset

, then the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 under 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $T(S)=\{T(s):s\in S\}$
\end_inset

.
 This definition typical in all of mathematics, not just linear algebra,
 and applies no matter the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand how the linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v})=A\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 affects areas, it is convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a product of elementary matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=E_{p}\cdots E_{2}E_{1}$
\end_inset

, as we have done before assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible (page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "par:M-as-a-product"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(S)=(T_{E_{p}}\circ\cdots\circ T_{E_{2}}\circ T_{E_{1}})(S)$
\end_inset

, if we can understand how linear transformations associated with elementary
 matrices affect area, we have a chance of understanding how general linear
 transformations affect area.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a row swap matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

 is a reflection about the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

, so in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 Reflections do not change areas.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a row replace matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

 is a shear transformation, and it is a known result of calculus that shear
 transformations do not affect area, so again 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a row scale matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

 scales shapes either horizontally or vertically—not both!—by a factor of
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=|s|\cdot\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 In every case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{E}(S))=|\det E|\cdot\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
 Remember, the determinant of a row swap matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, the determinant of a row replace matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and the determinant of a row scale matrix with scale factor 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{area}\left(T_{A}(S)\right) & =\text{area}\left((T_{E_{p}}\circ\cdots\circ T_{E_{2}}\circ T_{E_{1}})(S)\right)\\
 & =\text{area}\left(T_{E_{p}}\left(\cdots\left(T_{E_{2}}\left(T_{E_{1}}(S)\right)\right)\cdots\right)\right)\\
 & =|\det E_{p}|\cdots|\det E_{2}|\cdot|\det E_{1}|\cdot\text{area}(S)\\
 & =|\det A|\cdot\text{area}(S).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is noninvertible, then one of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of the other, so any linear combination of the columns is
 also a multiple of that column.
 Therefore, the image of any vector, which is a linear combination of the
 columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, is a multiple of that column.
 Thus the image of every vector lies on the line determined by that column,
 giving the image of any shape area zero.
 The entire image is contained within a line.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\det A|=0$
\end_inset

, so again we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{A}(S))=|\det A|\cdot\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Areas and eigenvalues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix with linearly independent eigenpairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2},\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v}_{1})=\lambda_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v}_{2})=\lambda_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{\mathbf{v}_{1}+\alpha\mathbf{v}_{2}:0\leq\alpha\leq1\}$
\end_inset

, the line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}+\mathbf{\mathbf{v}}_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(S)=\{T_{A}(\mathbf{v}_{1}+\alpha\mathbf{v}_{2}):0\leq\alpha\leq1\}=\{\lambda_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+\alpha\lambda_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}:0\leq\alpha\leq1\}$
\end_inset

 is the line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v}_{1})$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v}_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Further analysis shows that the image of the parallelogram determined by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the parallelogram determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v}_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(\mathbf{v}_{2})$
\end_inset

.
