\begin_layout Standard
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be the parallelogram determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}$
\end_inset

 scales 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 direction by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

 direction by factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the area of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}(P)$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $|\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}|$
\end_inset

 times the area of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 Since we have been arguing that linear transformations scale the areas
 of all shapes the same way, we have generally that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{area}(T_{A}(S))=|\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}|\cdot\text{area}(S)$
\end_inset

 for any shape whose area is measurable.
 With respect to the eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}$
\end_inset

 is a simple scaling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{area}(T_{A}(S)) & =|\det A|\cdot\text{area}(S)\\
 & \text{and}\\
\text{area}(T_{A}(S)) & =|\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}|\cdot\text{area}(S).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

It must be, then, that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\det A|=|\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}|$
\end_inset

.
 This is true for any 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix including noninvertible ones, but the statement can be made much
 stronger, as in the following theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Determinant-Eigenvalues"

\end_inset


\series bold
\shape up
[Determinant and the Product of Eigenvalues]
\series default
\shape default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2},\ldots,\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 are its 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (possibly complex) eigenvalues, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det A=\prod_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_{i}=\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}\cdots\lambda_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Some but not all parts of the justification of this theorem are straightforward.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular, then the conclusion follows quickly.
 As we have seen, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A$
\end_inset

 is the product of the entries on the main diagonal.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=\prod_{i=1}^{n}A_{i,i}$
\end_inset

.
 The characteristic equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\det(A-\lambda I)\\
 & =\det\left(\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
A_{1,1}-\lambda & \star & \cdots & \star\\
0 & A_{2,2}-\lambda & \cdots & \star\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & 0 & A_{n,n}-\lambda
\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =(A_{1,1}-\lambda)(A_{2,2}-\lambda)\cdots(A_{n,n}-\lambda)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

has solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1,1},A_{2,2},\ldots,A_{n,n}$
\end_inset

, so the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are the entries on the main diagonal of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{n}A_{i,i}=\prod_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 completing the proof for upper triangular matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is any matrix, the conclusion follows from two facts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The determinant and eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-1}AP$
\end_inset

 are the same as the determinant and eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 for any invertible 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-1}AP$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming these facts true for a moment, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U=P^{-1}AP$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=\det U$
\end_inset

 and the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by fact 1.
 Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is that special matrix such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular, as guaranteed to exist by fact 2, then the determinant
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (which equals the determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) and the product of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (which equals the product of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) are both 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{n}U_{i,i}$
\end_inset

 and therefore equal.
 This concludes the proof of the theorem for general matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Justification of fact 2 takes a bit of work (see crumpet 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "dig:triangularization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

