 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}_{1},\mathbf{u}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{u}_{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 This set can always be found since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 must have at least one nonzero entry (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 is not a permissible eigenvector).
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{i,1}\neq0$
\end_inset

, we may take 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{v},\mathbf{u}_{1},\mathbf{u}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{u}_{n-1}\}=\{\mathbf{v}\}\cup\{I_{:,j}:j\neq i\}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
\mathbf{v} & \mathbf{u}_{1} & \mathbf{u}_{2} & \cdots & \mathbf{u}_{n-1}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is invertible (its columns are linearly independent), and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q^{-1}AQ & =Q^{-1}A\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
\mathbf{v} & \mathbf{u}_{1} & \mathbf{u}_{2} & \cdots & \mathbf{u}_{n-1}\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
Q^{-1}A\mathbf{v} & Q^{-1}A\mathbf{u}_{1} & Q^{-1}A\mathbf{u}_{2} & \cdots & Q^{-1}A\mathbf{u}_{n-1}\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
\lambda Q^{-1}\mathbf{v} & Q^{-1}A\mathbf{u}_{1} & Q^{-1}A\mathbf{u}_{2} & \cdots & Q^{-1}A\mathbf{u}_{n-1}\end{array}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

While we cannot say much about 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{-1}A\mathbf{u}_{j}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, we can say 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda Q^{-1}\mathbf{v}=\lambda I_{:,1}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{-1}Q=Q^{-1}\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
\mathbf{v} & \mathbf{u}_{1} & \mathbf{u}_{2} & \cdots & \mathbf{u}_{n-1}\end{array}\right]=I$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{-1}$
\end_inset

 times the first column of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 must be the first column of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Hence we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q^{-1}AQ=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
\lambda & \star & \star & \star & \star\\
0 & \star & \star & \star & \star\\
0 & \star & \star & \star & \star\\
\vdots & \star & \star & \star & \star\\
0 & \star & \star & \star & \star
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

By the inductive hypothesis, there is a triangularization of 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q^{-1}AQ)_{\backslash1,1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}(Q^{-1}AQ)_{\backslash1,1}R$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & R
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & R^{-1}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{Q}^{-1}(Q^{-1}AQ)\hat{Q}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & R^{-1}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda & \star\\
0 & (Q^{-1}AQ)_{\backslash1,1}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & R
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

is upper triangular.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q\hat{Q})^{-1}A(Q\hat{Q})$
\end_inset

 is a triangularization of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This result suffices for our purposes, but the result can be strengthened
 to specify that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q\hat{Q})$
\end_inset

 have a certain property, a so-called Schur decomposition.
