\begin_layout Standard
Hence we have two ways to measure the effect of a linear transformation
 on the plane.
 In rough terms, a linear transformation expands or compresses areas by
 a factor equal to the absolute value of the determinant (which is equal
 to the absolute value of the product of the eigenvalues) of its standard
 matrix.
 More precisely a linear transformation expands or compresses areas in the
 direction of each eigenvector by a factor equal to the absolute value of
 the associated eigenvalue.
\end_layout

